vegetation, indigenous peoples (with special attention to their impact on past and present vegetation), and geologic history. From the great Panamanian isthmus to the boreal connections across the North Atlantic and North Pacific Oceans that allowed exchange of organisms between North America, Europe, and Asia, Graham’s sweeping, one-hundred-million-year history offers new insight into the forces that shaped the life and land of the New World.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBiogeographyxWestern Hemisphere. 0aBiogeographyzWestern Hemisphere. 0aLandformsxWestern Hemisphere. 0aLandformszWestern Hemisphere. 0aNatural bridgesxWestern Hemisphere. 0aNatural bridgeszWestern Hemisphere. 0aPlant diversityxWestern Hemisphere. 0aPlant diversityzWestern Hemisphere. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAntillean.  aBering.  aCenozoic.  aCentral American.  aCretaceous.  aMagellan.  aNew World.  aNorth Atlantic.  aclimate.  aland bridges.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022654415140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226544328423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226544328/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles